{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "I wish to suggest a new sort of criticism of Rule Consequentialism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The criticism will be friendly, since I do not claim that Rule Consequentialism is on the wrong track altogether, but instead that it is wrong in detail.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "My argument is quite simple, and it depends on two claims.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The first is that Rule Consequentialism is best understood as a theory of pattern-based reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The second claim is that, thus understood, Rule Consequentialism is distinguished by an account of the importance of such reasons that is very hard to accept.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "So, believers in Rule Consequentialism should drop this account, and embrace some other theory of pattern-based reasons -or, more radically, reject pattern-based reasons altogether.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Compliance-based Rule Consequentialism is best understood as a theory of pattern-based reasons; plausible versions of this theory will be pluralist, in the sense that they recognise act-based reasons as well as pattern-based reasons; but these versions are inferior to other pluralist theories of pattern-based reasons that give a messier, more plausible account of the interaction between act-based and pattern-based reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "So, nobody should believe in compliance-based Rule Consequentialism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "They should perhaps believe in some close but less tidy relative of it.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
